# Security Review: app.js

I reviewed the file. It is a very small Express app (~22 lines) with two unauthenticated GET endpoints and a listener on port 3000. Most "OWASP Top 10" concerns you asked about don't apply directly because there's no user input being parsed, no database, no auth layer, and no file/command execution. That said, here are the real issues and hardening recommendations.

## Findings

### 1. A01 — Broken Access Control / PII exposure on `/users`
The `/users` endpoint returns user data (including email addresses) with no authentication or authorization. Emails are PII. In production this would leak user data to anonymous callers.

**Recommendation:** require auth and scope the response.
```js
const requireAuth = (req, res, next) => {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace('Bearer ', '');
  if (!token || !isValidToken(token)) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });
  req.user = decodeToken(token);
  next();
};

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Only return fields the caller is allowed to see
  res.json(users.map(u => ({ id: u.id, name: u.name })));
});
```

### 2. A05 — Security Misconfiguration: no security headers
No `helmet()` usage. Express serves responses with `X-Powered-By: Express` and none of the standard hardening headers (CSP, HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy).

**Recommendation:**
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 3. A05 — No CORS policy
CORS is not configured. Depending on deployment, browsers may or may not reach this. Be explicit rather than relying on default behavior.
```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend.example.com'], methods: ['GET'] }));
```

### 4. A04 — No rate limiting / DoS protection
Any client can hit `/health` or `/users` unbounded. Add a rate limiter, especially for unauthenticated endpoints.
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 60 }));
```

### 5. A09 — No logging or error handling middleware
There's no request logger and no error handler. Unhandled exceptions will produce default Express stack traces (information disclosure in non-production `NODE_ENV`).
```js
