The `/users` endpoint returns user data (including email addresses) to any unauthenticated caller. Emails are PII under GDPR/CCPA. If this is intended to be public sample data, it's fine; if it represents a real users list, it's a problem.

**Recommendation** — add an auth middleware:
```js
function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace(/^Bearer\s+/i, '');
  if (!token || !isValidToken(token)) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });
  }
  next();
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => { /* ... */ });
```

### 2. Missing security headers (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration)
No `helmet` or equivalent. Responses ship without `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, CSP, etc.

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 3. No rate limiting (OWASP A04: Insecure Design)
Any client can hit `/users` or `/health` in a loop — useful for enumeration or DoS.

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));
```

### 4. No CORS policy declared
If a browser ever calls this API, you'll want an explicit allowlist rather than relying on defaults.

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend.example'] }));
```

### 5. Unstructured error handling / no 404 handler
There is no `app.use((err, req, res, next) => …)` nor a catch-all 404. Future routes that throw will leak stack traces via Express's default error handler in development.

```js
